    "discriminators": [
     "Shrill and HIGH: a near-pure tone with the overwhelming majority of its energy above 2 kHz and almost nothing below 200 Hz. Few partials, very low spectral_flatness.",
     "The pea is the real cue. A referee or police whistle has a cork or plastic pea rattling inside the chamber, which chops the tone into a fast warble — a large spectral_centroid_deviation_hz riding on an otherwise steady, sustained pitch. Nothing else in UCS produces that combination, and a human whistle certainly cannot.",
     "Harder onset and far less pitch-glide than WHISTLES-HUMAN, which drifts and swoops.",
     "Steam kettle and train whistles carry audible breath/steam noise (raised spectral_flatness) and often sound two pitches at once; a locomotive whistle captured as part of the train belongs to TRAINS-HORN.",
     "Every horn is an octave or more below this with a dense partial comb — pitch and partial_count separate the two families outright."
    ],
